##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedNumeric");

@fracs=([],[],[]);
$fracs[0][0]=random(100,500,1);
$fracs[0][1]=$fracs[0][0];
$fracs[0][2]=1;

$fracs[1][0]=random(100,500,1);
$fracs[1][1]=1;
$fracs[1][2]=$fracs[1][0];

if (random(0,1,1)==0) {($fracs[0],$fracs[1])=($fracs[1],$fracs[0]);}

$num0=$fracs[0][0];
$den0=$fracs[0][1];
$ans0=$fracs[0][2];

$num1=$fracs[1][0];
$den1=$fracs[1][1];
$ans1=$fracs[1][2];

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Reduce the following fractions: 

a.    [`` \frac{[$num0]}{[$den0]} =``][_________]{$ans0}

a.    [`` \frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} =``][_________]{$ans1}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The fraction line is like the division symbol. We have:

a.    [`` \frac{[$num0]}{[$den0]} = [$num0] \div [$den0] = [$ans0] ``]

a.    [`` \frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} = [$num1] \div [$den1] = [$ans1] ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();
